<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-1">
  <title>Matrix Addition</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Matrices of the same size can be added entry‑wise.  
      Compute
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 3\\2 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}
        +
        \begin{bmatrix}4 \amp -1\\1 \amp 5\end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{bmatrix}5 \amp 2\\3 \amp 5\end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — addition is performed entry‑wise.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 2\\1 \amp 5\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — the (1,1) and (2,1) entries are incorrect.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}4 \amp 3\\2 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — this is just the second matrix replaced incorrectly.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-2">
  <title>Scalar Multiplication</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute
      <m>
        3\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1\\4 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}.
      </m>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}6 \amp -3\\12 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — scalar multiplication multiplies each entry by the scalar.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}5 \amp -2\\7 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — each entry must be multiplied by 3.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}6 \amp -1\\4 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — only some entries were scaled.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-3">
  <title>Matrix Multiplication (2×2)</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Matrix multiplication is <em>not</em> entry‑wise but uses row‑by‑column combinations.  
      Compute
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2\\3 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}
        \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 0\\1 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}4 \amp 8\\7 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
          Row 1 · Col 1: 1·2 + 2·1 = 4.  
          Row 1 · Col 2: 1·0 + 2·4 = 8.  
          Row 2 · Col 1: 3·2 + 1·1 = 7.  
          Row 2 · Col 2: 3·0 + 1·4 = 4.  
          This follows the matrix‑product rule.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 8\\3 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No — the (1,1) and (2,1) entries are wrong.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 6\\5 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No — this incorrectly mixes entry‑wise multiplication.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-4">
  <title>Identity Matrix</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The identity matrix <m>I</m> is the matrix that leaves any vector unchanged.  
      Which of the following is the 3×3 identity matrix?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1
            \end{bmatrix}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
          The identity matrix has 1s on the diagonal and 0s elsewhere.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1
            \end{bmatrix}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No — that matrix does not act as an identity.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
            1 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0
            \end{bmatrix}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No — this is not the identity matrix.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-5">
  <title>When Is Matrix Multiplication Defined?</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The product <m>AB</m> is defined only when:
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>The number of columns of <m>A</m> equals the number of rows of <m>B</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — matrix multiplication requires the inner dimensions to match.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>A</m> and <m>B</m> must be square matrices.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — multiplication does not require square matrices.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The number of rows of <m>A</m> must equal the number of rows of <m>B</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — rows do not determine the rule.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matrix-dotproduct-relationship">
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the relationship between the dot product and matrix multiplication?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      If we regard vectors as column vectors, then for <m>\vec{x},\vec{y}\in\mathbb{R}^n</m> the dot product is
    </p>
    <me>
      \vec{x}\cdot\vec{y} \;=\; \vec{x}^{\,T}\vec{y},
    </me>
    <p>
      i.e., it is the matrix product of the row vector <m>\vec{x}^{\,T}</m> with the column vector <m>\vec{y}</m>.
      More generally, the <m>(i,j)</m> entry of a product <m>AB</m> is the dot product of row <m>i</m> of <m>A</m> with column <m>j</m> of <m>B</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matrix-column-vs-matrix-multiplication">
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the relationship between the product of a matrix <m>A</m> and a column vector and the product of <m>A</m> with another matrix <m>B</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      If <m>\vec{x}</m> is a column vector, we can treat it as a matrix with one column, so <m>A\vec{x} = A[\vec{x}]</m> is just a special case of matrix multiplication.
      More generally, if <m>B=[\vec{b}_1\ \vec{b}_2\ \cdots\ \vec{b}_k]</m>, then
    </p>
    <me>
      AB \;=\; \big[\,A\vec{b}_1\ \ A\vec{b}_2\ \ \cdots\ \ A\vec{b}_k\,\big],
    </me>
    <p>
      i.e., the columns of <m>AB</m> are the images of the columns of <m>B</m> under multiplication by <m>A</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="nonzero-not-necessarily-invertible">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Are all <em>nonzero</em> matrices invertible? If not, give an example.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      No. A nonzero matrix can be singular (noninvertible). For example,
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 0\\
      0 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}
    </me>
    <p>
      is nonzero but not invertible (its determinant is <m>0</m>).
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="scale-and-add-matrices">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Define
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}4 \amp -2\\ 3 \amp -5\\ 0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>
      and
      <m>B=\begin{bmatrix}-4 \amp 2\\ -24 \amp 26\\ 6 \amp -7\end{bmatrix}</m>.
      Compute <m>3A</m> and <m>A+B</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Scalar multiplication:
    </p>
    <me>
      3A
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      12 \amp -6\\
      9 \amp -15\\
      0 \amp 3
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
    <p>
      Entry‑wise addition:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> A+B
      \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      4+(-4) \amp -2+2\\
      3+(-24) \amp -5+26\\
      0+6 \amp 1+(-7)
      \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      0 \amp 0\\
      -21 \amp 21\\
      6 \amp -6
      \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
    </md>
  </solution>
</exercise>



<exercise xml:id="sizes-of-AB-and-BA">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>A</m> is <m>4\times 3</m> and <m>B</m> is <m>3\times 2</m>, what are the sizes of <m>AB</m> and <m>BA</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      The product <m>AB</m> is defined (inner dimensions match: 3) and has size <m>4\times 2</m>.
      The product <m>BA</m> is <em>not defined</em> because the inner dimensions would be <m>2</m> (from <m>B</m>) and <m>4</m> (from <m>A</m>), which do not match.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="compute-AB-2x3-by-3x2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 3 \amp 6\\ -1 \amp 0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>
      and
      <m>B=\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -3\\ 0 \amp 1\\ 4 \amp -7\end{bmatrix}</m>.
      Compute <m>AB</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Multiply (2×3) by (3×2) to obtain a (2×2) matrix:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> AB
      \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      2\cdot 2 + 3\cdot 0 + 6\cdot 4 \amp 2\cdot(-3) + 3\cdot 1 + 6\cdot(-7)\\
      (-1)\cdot 2 + 0\cdot 0 + 1\cdot 4 \amp (-1)\cdot(-3) + 0\cdot 1 + 1\cdot(-7)
      \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      28 \amp -45\\
      2 \amp -4
      \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
    </md>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="AB-not-equal-BA-example">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 6\end{bmatrix}</m>
      and
      <m>B=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0\\ 1 \amp 0\\ -1 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}</m>
      to demonstrate that <m>AB \ne BA</m> can happen.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      First, compute
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> AB
      \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1\cdot 1 + 2\cdot 1 + 3\cdot(-1) \amp 1\cdot 0 + 2\cdot 0 + 3\cdot(-1)\\
      4\cdot 1 + 5\cdot 1 + 6\cdot(-1) \amp 4\cdot 0 + 5\cdot 0 + 6\cdot(-1)
      \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      0 \amp -3\\
      3 \amp -6
      \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      Next, compute
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> BA
      \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 0\\ 1 \amp 0\\ -1 \amp -1
      \end{bmatrix}
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\ 4 \amp 5 \amp 6
      \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
      1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
      -5 \amp -7 \amp -9
      \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      Since <m>AB</m> is <m>2\times 2</m> while <m>BA</m> is <m>3\times 3</m> (and the entries differ), clearly <m>AB\ne BA</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="transpose-and-product-check">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let
      <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2 \amp 0\\ 3 \amp 0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>
      and
      <m>B=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2\\ 0 \amp 1\\ -2 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}</m>.
      Compute <m>AB</m>, <m>(AB)^{T}</m>, <m>A^{T}B^{T}</m>, and <m>B^{T}A^{T}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><strong>Product</strong> (2×3 by 3×2 gives 2×2):</p>
    <md>
      <mrow> AB
      \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1\cdot 1 + 2\cdot 0 + 0\cdot(-2) \amp 1\cdot 2 + 2\cdot 1 + 0\cdot 4\\
      3\cdot 1 + 0\cdot 0 + 1\cdot(-2) \amp 3\cdot 2 + 0\cdot 1 + 1\cdot 4
      \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 4\\
      1 \amp 10
      \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
    </md>
    <p><strong>Transpose:</strong></p>
    <me>
      (AB)^{T} = 
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 1\\
      4 \amp 10
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
    <p><strong>Compute</strong> <m>A^{T}</m> and <m>B^{T}</m>:</p>
    <me>
      A^{T}=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 3\\ 2 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix},\qquad
      B^{T}=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp -2\\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
    <p><strong>Products</strong> <m>A^{T}B^{T}</m> and <m>B^{T}A^{T}</m>:</p>
    <me>
       A^{T}B^{T}
        =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      7 \amp 3 \amp 10\\
      2 \amp 0 \amp -4\\
      2 \amp 1 \amp 4
      \end{bmatrix},
      \qquad
      B^{T}A^{T}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 1\\
      4 \amp 10
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
    <p>
      Note that <m>B^{T}A^{T}=(AB)^{T}</m>, illustrating the identity <m>(AB)^{T}=B^{T}A^{T}</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives42">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
Explain conceptually how matrix multiplication corresponds to composition
      of linear mappings.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p> 
Analyze examples illustrating how matrix operations affect the resulting
      action on vectors, using algebraic structure to justify results rather
      than computation alone.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
Relate familiar 1×1 mappings to higher‑dimensional cases and generalize
      the underlying algebraic principles to arbitrary matrix sizes.

            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>